	  <texsupport href="../LinearAlgebraTeXSupport.xml"/>
	
	  <title>Orientation in General: Examples</title>
	
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Describe possible orientations of a 1-dimensional subspace <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math> of <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[k]</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Discussion">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>A 1-dimensional subspace <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math> of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[k]</latex>
                     </math> is just a line through the origin. Therefore, an ordered basis of <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math> consists just of a single nonzero vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{b}</latex>
                     </math> in <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math>. It determines a direction of `increasing' in <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math>, together with its opposite: a direction of decreasing.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
	
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Describe possible orientations of a 2-dimensional subspace <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math> of <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[k]</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Discussion">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>A 2-dimensional subspace <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math> of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[k]</latex>
                     </math> is a plane passing through the origin. Therefore, an ordered basis of <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math> consists of an ordered pair of linearly independent vectors <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{B} = (\Vect{a} , \Vect{b} )</latex>
                     </math> in <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math>. Such a pair of vectors determines a preferred direction of rotation about a point, namely the shorter of the two possible trips from <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{a}</latex>
                     </math> to <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{b}</latex>
                     </math>. This direction of rotation is taken to be the ‘positive’ direction of rotation. The opposite direction of rotation is taken to be the negative direction of orientation.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
</showme.pack>
